DOS ([/dɒs/](/Help:IPA/English), [/dɔːs/](/Help:IPA/English)) is, or rather, *was*, a prominent family of [disk-based operating systems](/Disk_operating_system) specifically engineered for [IBM PC compatible](/IBM_PC_compatible) computers. It’s a name that conjures images of green text on black screens, a bygone era when computers demanded a certain level of... *engagement* from their users, rather than simply presenting a pretty facade. The DOS family, in its most commonly understood iteration, primarily comprised [IBM PC DOS](/IBM_PC_DOS) and its ubiquitous, somewhat aggressively rebranded sibling, [Microsoft](/Microsoft)'s [MS-DOS](/MS-DOS). Both of these contenders first graced the nascent personal computing scene in the auspicious year of 1981, setting the stage for a technological revolution, or at least a lot of frustrated users trying to remember arcane commands.

Following in their wake, a host of other manufacturers, keen to carve out their own slice of the expanding market, released compatible systems. These included [DR-DOS](/DR-DOS) in 1988, [ROM-DOS](/ROM-DOS) in 1989, [PTS-DOS](/PTS-DOS) in 1993, and the enduring, open-source spirit of [FreeDOS](/FreeDOS) in 1994. For a solid decade and a half, specifically between 1981 and 1995, [MS-DOS](/MS-DOS) held an almost undisputed reign over the [IBM PC compatible](/IBM_PC_compatible) market, becoming the de facto standard for personal computing and, for many, the very definition of a computer's "brain."

It’s important to note, though often overlooked by those with a shorter memory or a less cynical perspective, that "DOS" is merely a platform-independent acronym for "[disk operating system](/Disk_operating_system)." Its usage, in fact, predates the rise of the [IBM PC](/IBM_Personal_Computer) by a considerable margin. Dozens of other operating systems, hailing from various computing ecosystems, also bore this functional, if somewhat uninspired, acronym. This lineage stretches back to the colossal mainframe [DOS/360](/DOS/360_and_successors) from 1966. Beyond that, the acronym graced systems like [Apple DOS](/Apple_DOS), [Apple ProDOS](/Apple_ProDOS), [Atari DOS](/Atari_DOS), [Commodore DOS](/Commodore_DOS), [TRSDOS](/TRSDOS), and even the more sophisticated [AmigaDOS](/AmigaDOS). Each, in its own way, managed the fundamental interaction between software and storage, proving that sometimes, the simplest names are the most broadly applicable, even if they lack a certain flair.

## History

For those with an insatiable appetite for the minutiae of operating system lineages, there's further information available in the [Comparison of DOS operating systems](/Comparison_of_DOS_operating_systems) and the [Timeline of DOS operating systems](/Timeline_of_DOS_operating_systems). Consider it homework.

### Origins

The story of DOS, as most people understand it, begins not with some grand vision, but with a series of somewhat awkward corporate negotiations and a dash of opportunistic acquisition. [Apple CP/M](/Apple_CP/M) from [Digital Research](/Digital_Research) running on a [Z-80 SoftCard](/Z-80_SoftCard) for the [Apple II](/Apple_II) represents a significant predecessor, hinting at the architectural influences that would shape the future.

The foundational systems of the [IBM PC DOS](/IBM_PC_DOS) family (and its commercially distinct, separately sold counterpart, [MS-DOS](/MS-DOS)), along with their direct progenitor, [86-DOS](/86-DOS), were meticulously crafted to operate on the nascent [Intel 8086](/Intel_8086) [16-bit](/16-bit) processors. The development philosophy was rather pragmatic: to emulate the operational characteristics of [Digital Research](/Digital_Research)'s [CP/M](/CP/M). Why, you ask? Because [CP/M](/CP/M) was, at the time, the undisputed heavyweight champion of [disk operating systems](/Disk_operating_system) for the preceding generation of [8-bit](/8-bit) microcomputers, powered by [Intel 8080](/Intel_8080) and [Zilog Z80](/Zilog_Z80) [microprocessors](/Microprocessor). This design choice wasn't born of creative genius, but rather a calculated move to significantly simplify the porting of existing [CP/M](/CP/M) applications to the newer [MS-DOS](/MS-DOS) platform, thereby ensuring a ready-made software ecosystem for the burgeoning [IBM PC](/IBM_Personal_Computer).

The arrival of the [IBM Personal Computer](/IBM_Personal_Computer) (specifically, the IBM 5150 PC), built around the then-revolutionary [Intel 8088](/Intel_8088) [microprocessor](/Microprocessor), created an immediate and pressing need for a suitable operating system. Enter the corporate theater. [IBM](/IBM) Chairman [John Opel](/John_Opel), in what might be described as an early example of networking prowess, had a rather serendipitous conversation with fellow United Way National Board Executive Committee member [Mary Maxwell Gates](/Mary_Maxwell_Gates). She, in turn, directed Opel to her son, a young man named [Bill Gates](/Bill_Gates), who was then tasked with the seemingly straightforward request of securing an [8088](/Intel_8088)-compatible iteration of [CP/M](/CP/M).

IBM's initial foray into securing an operating system led them directly to [Digital Research](/Digital_Research), the rightful proprietors of [CP/M](/CP/M). A meeting was duly arranged, presumably accompanied by the usual corporate pleasantries. However, these initial negotiations quickly devolved into a stalemate. [Digital Research](/Digital_Research) harbored the rather reasonable expectation of selling [CP/M](/CP/M) on a royalty basis, a common practice for software licensing at the time. [IBM](/IBM), ever the monolith, envisioned a different arrangement: a single, flat license fee, coupled with the desire to rename the system to "PC DOS." [Digital Research](/Digital_Research) founder [Gary Kildall](/Gary_Kildall), reportedly a man of principle (or perhaps just a shrewd businessman who understood the value of his creation), flatly refused [IBM](/IBM)'s terms. And so, [IBM](/IBM) withdrew, leaving an opportunity gaping wide open.

A [simulated [SCP](/Seattle_Computer_Products) [86-DOS](/86-DOS) session](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c2/86-DOS_1.00.png/220px-86-DOS_1.00.png)

Undeterred, [IBM](/IBM) circled back to [Bill Gates](/Bill_Gates), who, with characteristic agility, recognized the opening. Gates, in turn, approached [Seattle Computer Products](/Seattle_Computer_Products) (SCP). There, a programmer named [Tim Paterson](/Tim_Paterson) had already developed a variant of [CP/M-80](/CP/M-80), initially conceived as an internal tool to test SCP's new 16-bit [Intel 8086](/Intel_8086) [CPU](/Central_processing_unit) card for the [S-100 bus](/S-100_bus). This system, with a rather self-deprecating initial moniker of QDOS (Quick and Dirty Operating System), was subsequently refined and made commercially available as [86-DOS](/86-DOS). Microsoft, with a keen eye for opportunity and a reported US$50,000, swiftly acquired [86-DOS](/86-DOS). This acquisition proved to be one of the most pivotal moments in computing history, as [86-DOS](/86-DOS) was rebranded as the Microsoft Disk Operating System, or [MS-DOS](/MS-DOS), and officially introduced in 1981. The rest, as they say, is a history filled with antitrust lawsuits and unparalleled market dominance.

Within a mere year of its introduction, Microsoft, demonstrating an early mastery of licensing strategies, had successfully licensed [MS-DOS](/MS-DOS) to over 70 other companies. These [original equipment manufacturers](/Original_equipment_manufacturer) (OEMs) then supplied the operating system bundled with their own hardware, sometimes even under their proprietary names, such as [Zenith Data Systems](/Zenith_Data_Systems)'s [Z-DOS](/Z-DOS). Microsoft, however, soon tightened its grip, eventually mandating the use of the [MS-DOS](/MS-DOS) name, with the singular exception of the version developed for [IBM](/IBM) itself. [IBM](/IBM), meanwhile, continued to independently develop its own iteration, [PC DOS](/PC_DOS), specifically for the [IBM PC](/IBM_Personal_Computer) line.

The ghost of [Digital Research](/Digital_Research) eventually resurfaced. They became acutely aware that an operating system remarkably similar to their own [CP/M](/CP/M) was being peddled by [IBM](/IBM) – and, adding insult to injury, under the very name that [IBM](/IBM) had originally insisted upon for [CP/M](/CP/M). Legal action loomed. [IBM](/IBM)'s response was a masterclass in corporate maneuvering: they offered [PC](/IBM_PC) consumers a "choice" between [PC DOS](/PC_DOS) or [CP/M-86](/CP/M-86), [Kildall](/Gary_Kildall)'s 8086-compatible version. This "choice," however, was heavily skewed. [CP/M](/CP/M) was priced at an additional US$200 over [PC DOS](/PC_DOS), effectively ensuring that sales of [CP/M](/CP/M) remained negligible. Thus, [CP/M](/CP/M) faded into obscurity, and [MS-DOS](/MS-DOS) and [PC DOS](/PC_DOS) ascended to become the dominant, marketed operating systems for [PCs](/IBM_PC) and their compatible brethren. A cautionary tale, if ever there was one, about the intersection of innovation and market strategy.

Microsoft's initial strategy involved selling [MS-DOS](/MS-DOS) exclusively to [original equipment manufacturers](/Original_equipment_manufacturer) (OEMs). The rationale behind this approach was rooted in the nascent and somewhat fragmented landscape of early [personal computers](/IBM_Personal_Computer); not all of them achieved 100% [IBM PC compatibility](/IBM_PC_compatible). DOS, in its architectural design, featured a deliberate separation between the system-specific device driver code (famously encapsulated in [IO.SYS](/IO.SYS)) and the core DOS kernel (found in [MSDOS.SYS](/MSDOS.SYS)). To facilitate this, Microsoft provided an OEM Adaptation Kit (OAK), a toolkit that allowed OEMs to meticulously customize the device driver code to precisely match the unique hardware configurations of their respective systems. However, as the industry matured through the late 1980s and into the early 1990s, the vast majority of [PCs](/IBM_PC_compatible) began to adhere more strictly to [IBM PC](/IBM_Personal_Computer) standards. This standardization enabled Microsoft to shift its strategy, and starting with [MS-DOS 5.0](/MS-DOS_5.0), they began offering a retail version of [MS-DOS](/MS-DOS) directly to consumers.

In the mid-1980s, Microsoft, in a move that often gets overlooked, embarked on the development of a [multitasking version of DOS](/MS-DOS_4.0_(multitasking)). This particular iteration is typically referred to as "European MS-DOS 4" due to its primary development for [ICL](/International_Computers_Limited) and subsequent licensing to various European companies. This advanced version of DOS boasted several features that were far ahead of its time for the DOS ecosystem, including support for [preemptive multitasking](/Preemption_(computing)), shared memory, device helper services, and even [New Executable](/New_Executable) ("NE") format executables. Curiously, none of these specific multitasking features found their way into later, widely released versions of DOS. However, they weren't entirely discarded; these foundational concepts and code structures were ingeniously repurposed to form the very basis of the [OS/2 1.0](/OS/2_1.0) kernel. It’s crucial to distinguish this "European MS-DOS 4" from the more widely distributed [PC DOS 4.0](/PC_DOS_4.0), which was developed by [IBM](/IBM) and built upon the existing [DOS 3.3](/MS-DOS_3.3) codebase, lacking these advanced multitasking capabilities.

[Digital Research](/Digital_Research), bruised but not entirely broken by the [MS-DOS](/MS-DOS) ascendancy, made several valiant attempts to reclaim the market share it had lost with [CP/M-86](/CP/M-86). Their initial efforts included [Concurrent DOS](/Concurrent_DOS), [FlexOS](/FlexOS), and [DOS Plus](/DOS_Plus), all designed with a dual compatibility for both [MS-DOS](/MS-DOS) and [CP/M-86](/CP/M-86) software. Later, they ventured into [Multiuser DOS](/Multiuser_DOS), which also maintained compatibility with both [MS-DOS](/MS-DOS) and [CP/M-86](/CP/M-86) applications, and, most notably, [DR DOS](/DR_DOS), which focused on robust compatibility with [MS-DOS](/MS-DOS) software. [Digital Research](/Digital_Research) was eventually acquired by [Novell](/Novell), a transaction that saw [DR DOS](/DR_DOS) evolve into [PalmDOS](/PalmDOS) and [Novell DOS](/Novell_DOS). Its journey didn't end there, as it later became a part of [Caldera](/Caldera_(company)) (marketed under the names [OpenDOS](/OpenDOS) and [DR-DOS 7.02](/DR-DOS_7.02)/[7.03](/DR-DOS_7.03)), then [Lineo](/Lineo), and finally [DeviceLogics](/DeviceLogics), a testament to its enduring, if niche, appeal.

[Gordon Letwin](/Gordon_Letwin), a Microsoft engineer, famously remarked in 1995 that "DOS was, when we first wrote it, a one-time throw-away product intended to keep [IBM](/IBM) happy so that they'd buy our languages." A rather cynical, yet undeniably accurate, assessment of its initial intent. Microsoft, in its early strategic planning, fully anticipated that [MS-DOS](/MS-DOS) would serve as a mere interim solution, a placeholder before the grand introduction of [Xenix](/Xenix), their version of Unix. The company's long-term vision involved progressively refining [MS-DOS](/MS-DOS) until it became virtually indistinguishable from a single-user [Xenix](/Xenix), or [XEDOS](/XEDOS), which was also slated to run on diverse architectures such as the [Motorola 68000](/Motorola_68000), [Zilog Z-8000](/Zilog_Z-8000), and [LSI-11](/LSI-11). The ultimate goal was to ensure [upward compatibility](/Upward_compatible) with [Xenix](/Xenix), which [BYTE](/BYTE) magazine, in 1983, presciently described as "the multi-user [MS-DOS](/MS-DOS) of the future." It seems even the future isn’t what it used to be.

[OS/2](/OS/2) 1.0 featured a text mode interface similar to [MS-DOS](/MS-DOS).

[IBM](/IBM), however, proved rather resistant to the idea of simply replacing DOS. They had invested heavily, both financially and emotionally, in the platform. After [AT&T](/AT%26T) began to actively market and sell [Unix](/Unix), Microsoft and [IBM](/IBM), seeing a competitive threat and recognizing the limitations of DOS for future computing, began a joint venture to develop [OS/2](/OS/2) as a more advanced, graphical, and multitasking alternative. This partnership, however, was destined for acrimony. The two corporate giants eventually found themselves embroiled in a series of fundamental disagreements over the direction of two successor operating systems: [OS/2](/OS/2) and [Windows](/Microsoft_Windows). These irreconcilable differences ultimately led to a fractured development path, with each company pursuing its own vision for the future, effectively splitting the development of their respective DOS systems. The final retail version of [MS-DOS](/MS-DOS) was [MS-DOS 6.22](/MS-DOS_6.22). Following this, [MS-DOS](/MS-DOS) ceased to be a standalone product and became an integral, albeit hidden, component of [Windows 95](/Windows_95), [Windows 98](/Windows_98), and [Windows Me](/Windows_Me). Similarly, the last retail version of [PC DOS](/PC_DOS) was [PC DOS 2000](/PC_DOS_2000) (also known as [PC DOS 7 revision 1](/PC_DOS_7_revision_1)), though [IBM](/IBM) did continue to develop [PC DOS 7.10](/PC_DOS_7.10) for its OEMs and for internal use, demonstrating that some legacies simply refuse to die gracefully.

Amidst this corporate drama, a new, more idealistic movement began. The [FreeDOS](/FreeDOS) project, a beacon of open-source philosophy, commenced on 26 June 1994. This date was no coincidence; it was precisely when Microsoft, with the cold efficiency of a corporate titan moving on to greener pastures, announced it would no longer actively sell or support [MS-DOS](/MS-DOS). [Jim Hall](/Jim_Hall_(programmer)), a programmer with a vision, promptly posted a manifesto, proposing the collaborative development of an open-source replacement for [MS-DOS](/MS-DOS). Within a mere few weeks, other like-minded programmers, including [Pat Villani](/Pat_Villani) and Tim Norman, rallied to the cause. A functional kernel, the indispensable [COMMAND.COM](/COMMAND.COM) command-line interpreter (or "shell," for those who appreciate proper terminology), and a suite of essential core utilities were swiftly brought into existence by pooling code they had either personally written or found readily available under permissive licenses. After several official pre-release distributions, the inaugural [FreeDOS 1.0](/FreeDOS_1.0) distribution was finally unleashed upon the world on 3 September 2006. Released under the permissive [GNU General Public License](/GNU_General_Public_License) (GPL), [FreeDOS](/FreeDOS) proudly stands as a testament to community effort, requiring no license fees or royalties. It's almost... heartwarming. Almost.

### Decline

Main article: [History of Microsoft Windows](/History_of_Microsoft_Windows)

Early versions of [Microsoft Windows](/Microsoft_Windows) were not standalone operating systems; they were, in essence, sophisticated graphical shells that ran *on top* of [MS-DOS](/MS-DOS). They relied on DOS for fundamental services like file management and hardware access, much like a parasite relies on its host, albeit a mutually beneficial one for a time. By the early 1990s, the Windows graphical shell became an increasingly dominant feature on new computer systems, signaling a clear shift in user preference away from the stark command line. The pivotal moment arrived in 1995 with the release of [Windows 95](/Windows_95). This version was marketed and bundled as a standalone operating system, conspicuously *not* requiring a separate DOS license. [Windows 95](/Windows_95) (and its successors, [Windows 98](/Windows_98) and [Windows Me](/Windows_Me)) effectively took over as the default [OS kernel](/OS_kernel), relegating the [MS-DOS](/MS-DOS) component to a background role, primarily for backward compatibility with older applications and games. With [Windows 95](/Windows_95) and [Windows 98](/Windows_98) (though notably *not* [Windows Me](/Windows_Me)), the [MS-DOS](/MS-DOS) component retained the unique capability of being run independently, without initiating the full Windows graphical environment. This provided a lifeline for users who still preferred or needed direct access to the DOS command line. However, as DOS was no longer a prerequisite for using Windows, the vast majority of users, understandably, ceased interacting with it directly. It was a slow, inevitable fade into the background, like an old friend you occasionally remember but rarely call.

### Continued use

[DOSBox](/DOSBox)

As of 2025, if anyone is still bothering to update this, available compatible systems include [FreeDOS](/FreeDOS), [ROM-DOS](/ROM-DOS), [PTS-DOS](/PTS_DOS), RxDOS, and [REAL/32](/REAL/32). Surprisingly, some computer manufacturers, notably [Dell](/Dell) and [HP](/Hewlett-Packard), still ship machines with [FreeDOS](/FreeDOS) installed as an [OEM](/Original_equipment_manufacturer) operating system. This is often for low-cost systems or as a bare-bones platform for users who intend to install their own operating system. It’s a niche market, certainly, but one that persists. Furthermore, a dedicated cadre of developers and computer engineers continue to utilize DOS-based systems. Why? Because it offers a level of proximity to the underlying hardware that modern, abstracted operating systems simply don't. For certain specialized tasks, diagnostics, or low-level programming, the directness of DOS remains an undeniable, if anachronistic, advantage. It’s a testament to its fundamental design, or perhaps to humanity’s stubborn refusal to let go of perfectly functional, albeit ancient, tools.

#### Embedded systems

DOS's decidedly minimalist architecture and its direct approach to accessing hardware make it surprisingly well-suited for deployment in [embedded devices](/Embedded_system). This is a realm where efficiency, small footprint, and predictable, direct hardware control are paramount, and the overhead of a modern, feature-rich operating system is simply unacceptable. The final versions of [DR-DOS](/DR-DOS), for instance, were specifically refined and targeted at this enduring market segment, proving that old dogs can still learn a few new tricks if the incentive is right. As a notable example, [ROM-DOS](/ROM-DOS), another member of this resilient family, served as the operating system for the [Canon PowerShot Pro 70](/Canon_PowerShot_Pro), a digital camera that, in its time, was quite advanced. It’s a stark reminder that the digital world is far more diverse than the glossy interfaces of your average desktop suggest.

#### Emulation

For those who crave a taste of the past without actually dusting off an ancient machine, [emulation](/Emulator) provides a convenient, if somewhat sterile, experience. On [Linux](/Linux) systems, for example, it's entirely possible to run [DOSEMU](/DOSEMU), a Linux-native [virtual machine](/Virtual_machine) specifically designed for executing DOS programs at near-native speeds. It's like a digital time capsule, minus the actual dust. Beyond [DOSEMU](/DOSEMU), a plethora of other [emulators](/Emulator) exist, allowing users to run DOS applications on various versions of [Unix](/Unix) and, rather ironically, [Microsoft Windows](/Microsoft_Windows) itself. The most prominent among these is [DOSBox](/DOSBox). [DOSBox](/DOSBox) has become the go-to solution for preserving and playing classic DOS-era games (think pixelated masterpieces like [King's Quest](/King%27s_Quest) or the original, glorious [Doom](/Doom_(1993_video_game))) on contemporary operating systems. It’s a digital archeological dig, allowing you to experience the past without the hassle of configuring IRQ settings. [DOSBox](/DOSBox) itself includes its own robust implementation of DOS, which is intricately tied to the emulator and, therefore, cannot be run on actual physical hardware. However, it retains the flexibility to boot other genuine DOS operating systems, such as [MS-DOS](/MS-DOS) or [FreeDOS](/FreeDOS), if a specific scenario demands it.

## Design

[MS-DOS](/MS-DOS) and its related [IBM PC DOS](/IBM_PC_DOS) operating systems are inextricably linked with machines employing [Intel](/Intel) [x86](/X86) or compatible [CPUs](/CPU), predominantly the [IBM PC compatibles](/IBM_PC_compatible) that eventually flooded the market. However, it's worth noting that machine-dependent versions of [MS-DOS](/MS-DOS) were also produced for a multitude of non-IBM-compatible [x86](/X86)-based machines. These variations ranged from simple relabeling of the standard [Microsoft](/Microsoft) distribution under a manufacturer's own brand to highly specialized versions meticulously crafted to interface with unique, non-IBM-PC-compatible hardware. The genius of its design, if you can call it that, lay in its abstraction: as long as application programs conscientiously utilized the standard DOS [APIs](/API) rather than directly poking at hardware, they possessed the remarkable ability to execute flawlessly on both [IBM-PC-compatible](/IBM_PC_compatible) and incompatible machines. This adherence to a common interface was crucial for software portability. Interestingly, the original [FreeDOS](/FreeDOS) kernel, known as [DOS-C](/DOS-C), actually had its genesis in [DOS/NT](/DOS/NT), a system developed for the [Motorola 68000](/Motorola_68000) series of [CPUs](/CPU) in the early 1990s. While these systems shared a loose resemblance to the DOS architecture, applications were not binary compatible due to the fundamentally incompatible instruction sets of these non-[x86-CPUs](/X86). Nevertheless, applications written in higher-level programming languages could be ported with relative ease, a small mercy in a world of hardware-specific headaches.

At its core, DOS is a fundamentally minimalist operating system. It operates as a [single-user](/Single-user_operating_system), [single-tasking operating system](/Single-tasking_operating_system), meaning it was designed to execute one program for one user at any given moment. Its basic [kernel](/Kernel_(computer_science)) functions are inherently [non-reentrant](/Reentrant_(subroutine)): only a solitary program can leverage them at any single point in time, and the DOS kernel itself offers precisely zero built-in mechanisms to enable the simultaneous execution of multiple programs. The DOS kernel, in its elegant simplicity, provides a suite of [various functions for programs](/DOS_API) (an [application program interface](/API)) covering essential operations such as character I/O, rudimentary file management, memory management, and the loading and termination of programs. It was, in essence, a digital traffic cop, directing one vehicle at a time.

DOS, in a gesture towards rudimentary automation, offers the capability for [shell scripting](/Shell_script) through the use of [batch files](/Batch_file), easily identifiable by their ubiquitous [filename extension](/Filename_extension) of `.BAT`. Each line within a batch file is interpreted, in sequential order, as a distinct program command to be executed. Beyond simply launching external programs, batch files also possess the ability to harness internal commands, such as the ever-useful [GOTO](/GOTO) statement for flow control, and various [conditional statements](/Conditional_(programming)) that allow for rudimentary decision-making within a script. It was a simple, yet powerful, way to automate repetitive tasks, or at least to make your computer do your bidding without having to type every command manually.

The operating system provides a straightforward [application programming interface](/API) that facilitates the development of character-based applications. However, and this is a critical distinction, it offers almost no direct, abstracted access to the majority of the underlying [computer hardware](/Computer_hardware), such as [graphics cards](/Video_card), [printers](/Computer_printer), or [mice](/Computer_mouse). This architectural choice meant that programmers, in their relentless pursuit of performance and functionality, were often compelled to bypass the DOS [API](/API) entirely and access the hardware directly. This usually necessitated that each application carried its own bespoke set of [device drivers](/Device_driver) tailored for every conceivable hardware peripheral. Consequently, hardware manufacturers found themselves in a perpetual arms race, needing to release detailed specifications to ensure that device drivers for the most popular applications were readily available, lest their hardware be rendered useless by software incompatibility. It was a wild west of hardware interaction, where only the most determined programmers dared to tread.

### Boot sequence

The intricate ballet of a DOS system coming to life is, for the uninitiated, a marvel of low-level programming, and for the initiated, a tedious sequence of events you'd rather not think about.

*   The initial spark, the [bootstrap loader](/Bootstrap_loader) on [PC-compatible computers](/IBM_PC_compatible), is found within the [master boot record](/Master_boot_record) (MBR). This crucial piece of code resides precisely at the very beginning of the [boot sector](/Boot_sector), which is the first sector on the first track (known, rather poetically, as [track zero](/Track0)) of the designated boot disk. The system's [ROM BIOS](/BIOS) undertakes the critical task of loading this sector into memory, specifically at address `0000h:7C00h`. It then, with a touch of digital skepticism, typically verifies the presence of a signature "55h AAh" at memory offset `+1FEh`. If this signature is absent or invalid, the [ROM BIOS](/BIOS) will, with a sigh of resignation, attempt to boot from the next physical disk in its predefined sequence. If, however, the sector passes this rudimentary validation, the [BIOS](/BIOS) will then transfer execution to the loaded address, having thoughtfully configured certain registers for the next stage.

*   If the recently loaded boot sector happens to be a [Master Boot Record](/Master_Boot_Record) (MBR), as is the case for partitioned storage media, it performs a self-relocation maneuver. It moves its own code to memory address `0000h:0600h`. This step is, of course, bypassed if the loaded sector is not an MBR. The MBR code then meticulously scans the partition table, which is conveniently co-located within this very sector, in search of an active partition. Modern MBRs typically check if bit 7 is set at offset `+1BEh+10h*n` within the table, while their older counterparts simply looked for a value of `80h`. If an active partition is successfully identified, the MBR proceeds to load the very first sector of that corresponding partition – which, in turn, contains the [Volume Boot Record](/Volume_Boot_Record) (VBR) for that specific volume – into memory at `0000h:7C00h`. This loading process mirrors the initial load by the [ROM BIOS](/BIOS). The MBR then, with a final flourish, passes execution to this newly loaded portion, again ensuring that certain registers are appropriately configured.

*   The contents of the sector now residing at `0000h:7C00h` constitute the [Volume Boot Record](/Volume_Boot_Record) (VBR). VBRs are notoriously operating system specific; they are not generally interchangeable between different DOS versions, as their precise behavior and internal logic vary considerably. In the most ancient iterations of DOS, such as DOS 1.x, the VBR was responsible for loading the entirety of the [IO.SYS](/IO.SYS) (or [IBMBIO.COM](/IBMBIO.COM) for [IBM PC DOS](/IBM_PC_DOS)) file into memory at `0000h:0600h`. For this rather crude method to function, these system files absolutely *had* to be stored in consecutive sectors on the disk by the `SYS` utility. In later, more refined versions, the VBR would instead locate and store the contents of the first two entries in the root directory at `0000h:0500h`. If these entries correctly pointed to the designated boot files, as recorded within the VBR itself, the VBR would then load the first three *consecutive* sectors of the [IO.SYS](/IO.SYS)/[IBMBIO.COM](/IBMBIO.COM) file into memory at `0070h:0000h`. The VBR, ever diligent, also had to meticulously preserve the contents of the Disk Parameter Table (DPT). Finally, it would transfer control to this partially loaded portion by jumping to its entry point, once again with specific registers pre-configured – a process that, predictably, also exhibited considerable differences across various DOS versions.

*   In these later (and frankly, more complicated) DOS versions, where the VBR had only loaded a mere three sectors of the [IO.SYS](/IO.SYS)/[IBMBIO.COM](/IBMBIO.COM) file into memory, the loaded fragment itself contained a secondary boot loader. This sub-loader then took over, loading the *remainder* of its own code into memory, utilizing the root directory information that had been so carefully stored at `0000h:0500h`. For the vast majority of these versions, the file contents still stubbornly insisted on being stored in consecutive order on the disk. In the older DOS versions, which were loaded as a single, monolithic block, this entire step was mercifully skipped.

*   The DOS system initialization code then springs into action, diligently initializing its suite of built-in device drivers. Following this, it loads the core DOS kernel, typically found in [MSDOS.SYS](/MSDOS.SYS) on [MS-DOS](/MS-DOS) systems, into memory. In the [Windows 9x](/Windows_9x) era, this process saw a slight consolidation: the DOS system initialization code, its built-in device drivers, and the DOS kernel were all combined into a single, monolithic [IO.SYS](/IO.SYS) file, while [MSDOS.SYS](/MSDOS_SYS) itself was repurposed as a simple text-based configuration file.

*   Next, the venerable [CONFIG.SYS](/CONFIG.SYS) file is parsed, its lines meticulously read to extract vital configuration parameters. The `SHELL` variable, if present, specifies the exact location of the [command shell](/Shell_(computing)), which, in the absence of explicit instruction, defaults to the iconic [COMMAND.COM](/COMMAND.COM).

*   Finally, the designated [command shell](/Shell_(computing)) is loaded into memory and executed, presenting the user with the familiar command prompt.

*   As the final act of the boot sequence, the startup [batch file](/Batch_file), [AUTOEXEC.BAT](/AUTOEXEC.BAT), is then executed by the shell. This file, a series of commands executed automatically, was the primary means by which users customized their DOS environment, loading utilities, setting paths, and generally making the system tolerable.

A critical, and often frustrating, characteristic of early DOS versions is that the core DOS system files loaded by the boot sector absolutely *must* be [contiguous](/Fragmentation_(computer)) on the disk and occupy the first two [directory entries](/FAT_directory_table) in the root. This rigid requirement meant that merely removing and then re-adding these files would, with almost guaranteed certainty, render the storage media unbootable. It was a digital tightrope walk. However, the system did offer a degree of flexibility: it was entirely possible to replace the default shell at will, a common method employed to directly launch dedicated applications, bypassing the standard command prompt for a faster, more streamlined experience. This particular limitation, it should be noted, did not plague any version of [DR DOS](/DR_DOS), where the system files could be scattered anywhere within the root directory and did not demand contiguous storage. Consequently, [DR DOS](/DR_DOS) system files could be simply copied to a disk, provided the boot sector was already [DR DOS](/DR_DOS) compatible, a small but significant quality-of-life improvement.

In both [PC DOS](/PC_DOS) and [DR DOS 5.0](/DR_DOS_5.0) and later versions, the core DOS system files adopted different nomenclature: [IBMBIO.COM](/IBMBIO.COM) replaced [IO.SYS](/IO.SYS), and [IBMDOS.COM](/IBMDOS.COM) took the place of [MSDOS.SYS](/MSDOS_SYS). Older iterations of [DR DOS](/DR_DOS) utilized DRBIOS.SYS and DRBDOS.SYS, further adding to the delightful confusion of naming conventions.

Starting with [MS-DOS 7.0](/MS-DOS_7.0), which was essentially the DOS component embedded within [Windows 9x](/Windows_9x), a significant consolidation occurred. The binary system files [IO.SYS](/IO.SYS) and [MSDOS.SYS](/MSDOS_SYS) were merged into a single [IO.SYS](/IO.SYS) file. [MSDOS.SYS](/MSDOS_SYS) was then repurposed, transforming from a critical binary component into a simple text-based configuration file, much like [CONFIG.SYS](/CONFIG_SYS) and [AUTOEXEC.BAT](/AUTOEXEC.BAT). If the `BootGUI` directive within this new [MSDOS.SYS](/MSDOS_SYS) was explicitly set to `0`, the boot process would halt gracefully after loading the command processor (typically [COMMAND.COM](/COMMAND_COM)), rather than automatically launching `WIN.COM` and plunging the user into the graphical embrace of Windows. A small concession to those who still preferred the command line.

### File system

DOS, in its formative years, relied on a [file system](/File_system) that imposed a rather quaint and restrictive naming convention: the [8.3 filename](/8.3_filename). This meant files were limited to a maximum of eight characters for the primary filename, followed by an optional period and a maximum of three characters for the extension. It was a system that demanded brevity and, at times, creative abbreviations. With the advent of [DOS 2](/MS-DOS_2.0), a significant evolutionary step was taken: hierarchical directories were introduced. This allowed for a more organized file structure, moving beyond the flat, single-directory chaos of earlier versions. Each directory name, however, still adhered to the [8.3 format](/8.3_filename). Due to the internal Current Directory Structure (CDS) tables that DOS meticulously maintained, the maximum length of a full directory path was limited to 64 characters. When factoring in the drive name, the absolute maximum length of a fully qualified filename that DOS could support was 80 characters, following the familiar format `drive:\path\filename.ext`, terminated by a null byte. It was an exercise in digital conciseness.

The underlying architecture for DOS's file management was the venerable [File Allocation Table](/File_Allocation_Table) (FAT) [filesystem](/File_system). This began with [FAT12](/FAT12), a system that could manage up to 4078 clusters per drive, suitable for the relatively small storage capacities of the time. [DOS 3.0](/MS-DOS_3.0) brought a crucial enhancement with the introduction of [FAT16](/FAT16), which utilized 16-bit allocation entries, dramatically increasing the supported capacity to up to 65518 clusters per drive. A further refinement came with [Compaq MS-DOS 3.31](/Compaq_MS-DOS_3.31), which introduced support for [FAT16B](/FAT16B). This version courageously broke through the infamous 32-[MiB](/Mebibyte) drive limit, allowing support for hard drives up to a respectable 512 [MiB](/Mebibyte). Finally, with [MS-DOS 7.1](/MS-DOS_7.0) (the integrated DOS component found within [Windows 9x](/Windows_9x)), the file system evolved once more to embrace [FAT32](/FAT32). This used 32-bit allocation entries, pushing the boundaries of supported hard drive sizes to an impressive 137 GB (127 [GiB](/Gibibyte)) and beyond.

Starting with [DOS 3.1](/MS-DOS_3.1), a new capability was woven into the fabric of the operating system: file redirector support. This feature was initially conceived to facilitate networking capabilities, allowing DOS to interact with shared resources over a network. Its utility, however, extended beyond mere networking; it was later ingeniously repurposed to provide support for [CD-ROM drives](/Optical_disc_drive) through the now-legendary [MSCDEX](/MSCDEX) (Microsoft CD-ROM Extensions) program. [IBM PC DOS 4.0](/IBM_PC_DOS_4.0) also featured preliminary support for an installable file system (IFS), a forward-thinking concept that, regrettably, remained largely unused and was subsequently stripped out in [DOS 5.0](/MS-DOS_5.0). DOS also offered support for Block Devices, essentially "Disk Drive" devices that could be loaded via [CONFIG.SYS](/CONFIG.SYS) and integrated into the DOS file system to provide access to network devices, further expanding its capabilities in a nascent connected world.

### Drive naming scheme

Main article: [Drive letter assignment](/Drive_letter_assignment)

In the DOS universe, storage drives are identified by single, unambiguous identifying letters. The standard practice, almost a sacred tradition, was to reserve "A" and "B" exclusively for [floppy drives](/Floppy_drives). On systems equipped with only a single floppy drive, DOS, with a certain level of digital theatricality, would assign *both* letters to that solitary drive, prompting the user to engage in a rather analog act of "disk swapping" as programs alternated their access between the conceptual "A" and "B" drives. This ingenious, if cumbersome, mechanism facilitated tasks like copying data from one floppy to another, or running a program from one floppy disk while accessing its data from a second.

[Hard drives](/Hard_drives), the behemoths of early storage, were initially assigned the letters "C" and "D." DOS, in its early iterations, possessed a fundamental limitation: it could only support one active partition per physical drive. As support for an increasing number of hard drives became available, this scheme evolved. Drive letters were first allocated to each drive's active [primary partition](/Primary_partition). Then, a second pass was made over the drives to assign letters to any [logical drives](/Logical_partition) residing within an [extended partition](/Extended_partition). Finally, a third pass would grant names to any other non-active [primary partitions](/Primary_partition), provided such additional partitions existed and contained a DOS-supported [file system](/File_system). The grand finale of this letter assignment process involved allocating letters for [optical disc drives](/Optical_disc_drive), [RAM disks](/RAM_disk), and any other miscellaneous hardware. The order of letter assignments generally followed the sequence in which their respective drivers were loaded, though drivers themselves possessed the power to instruct DOS to assign a different, preferred letter; drivers for network drives, for example, typically claimed letters closer to the end of the alphabet, presumably to avoid conflicts with local storage.

The direct reliance of DOS applications on these hard-coded drive letters (a stark contrast to the more abstract `/dev` directory structure found in [Unix-like](/Unix-like) systems) presented a significant vulnerability to disruption. The simple act of adding new hardware that required a drive letter could throw the entire carefully constructed scheme into disarray. Consider, for instance, the addition of a new hard drive containing a primary partition, when a pre-existing hard drive already housed logical drives within extended partitions; the new drive would invariably snatch a letter that had previously been assigned to one of those extended partition logical drives. Even the seemingly innocuous act of adding a new hard drive containing *only* logical drives in an extended partition would still disrupt the established letters of [RAM disks](/RAM_disk) and [optical drives](/Optical_disc_drive). This persistent problem plagued Microsoft's DOS-based [Windows 9x](/Windows_9x) versions, enduring until they were finally superseded by operating systems based on the NT kernel line, which, thankfully, preserved the letters of existing drives until a user explicitly decided to change them. Under DOS, a common workaround for this digital chaos involved defining a `SUBST` drive and installing the problematic DOS program into this logical drive. The assignment of this `SUBST` drive could then be dynamically altered within a batch job whenever the application was launched, effectively sidestepping the rigid letter assignment. Under some versions of [Concurrent DOS](/Concurrent_DOS), as well as under [Multiuser DOS](/Multiuser_DOS), System Manager, and [REAL/32](/REAL/32), a reserved drive letter, `L:`, would be automatically assigned to the corresponding [load drive](/Load_drive) whenever an application started, offering a slightly more elegant solution.

### Reserved device names

Main article: [Device file](/Device_file)

"LPT1" redirects here. For underlying hardware, see [Parallel port](/Parallel_port).
"COM1" redirects here. For underlying hardware, see [Serial port](/Serial_port) and [COM (hardware interface)](/COM_(hardware_interface)).

[Error message when attempting to use a reserved name while naming or renaming a file or folder](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c8/Windows_Vista_Reserved_Name_Error.png/220px-Windows_Vista_Reserved_Name_Error.png)

In the strange and wonderful world of DOS, there exist certain [reserved](/Reserved_word) device names that, regardless of any accompanying extension, simply cannot be used as filenames. These names are pre-occupied by built-in character devices, hard-coded into the system's very fabric. These restrictions, surprisingly, continue to plague several versions of Windows, occasionally leading to system crashes and even, rather embarrassingly, security vulnerabilities. It’s a testament to how deeply ingrained these archaic design choices were.

The list of these sacred, untouchable names includes:

*   `COM1` through `COM9` (representing the [serial communication ports](/COM_(hardware_interface)), conduits for data that once connected modems and mice)
*   `LPT1` through `LPT9` (designating the [Parallel port](/Parallel_port), primarily for [line printers](/Line_printer), a relic of a time when printing was a noisy, mechanical affair)
*   `CON` (the "console"; a dual-purpose entity representing the keyboard for input [stream](/Stream_(computing)) and the display for output [stream](/Stream_(computing)))
*   `AUX` (the "auxiliary" device; typically an alias for the first connected [COM port](/COM_(hardware_interface)))
*   `PRN` (the "printer"; an alias for the first connected [LPT port](/Parallel_port))
*   `NUL` (the [null device](/Null_device), a digital black hole that consumes all output and produces nothing, mercifully added in [86-DOS](/86-DOS) 1.10 and [PC DOS](/PC_DOS) 1.0)

In the bewildering landscape of [Windows 95](/Windows_95) and [Windows 98](/Windows_98), attempting to navigate to the location of a reserved name (e.g., typing `CON/CON`, `AUX/AUX`, or `PRN/PRN` into the address bar) would, with predictable consistency, trigger a system crash. Microsoft, in a rare moment of acknowledging its own flaws, eventually provided a security fix for this rather glaring issue. [Windows XP](/Windows_XP), ever the smoother operator, handled this with more grace: any attempt to name a file or folder using a reserved name would silently revert to its previous name, offering no notification or error message – a quiet refusal rather than a dramatic collapse. By the time [Windows Vista](/Windows_Vista) and later versions arrived, the system had evolved to a more direct approach: attempting to use a reserved name for a file or folder would simply elicit an error message, stating, with polite firmness, "The specified device name is invalid."

These names (with the exception of `NUL`, which arrived a bit later) have been steadfastly supported across all versions of [MS-DOS](/MS-DOS), [PC DOS](/PC_DOS), and [DR-DOS](/DR-DOS) since their inception. `LST` was also available in certain [OEM](/Original_equipment_manufacturer) versions of [MS-DOS 1.25](/MS-DOS_1.25), while other OEM variants of the same version had already transitioned to `LPT1` (for the first [line printer](/Parallel_port)) and `COM1` (for the first [serial communication device](/COM_(hardware_interface))), as initially introduced with [PC DOS](/PC_DOS). In addition to `LPT1` and `LPT2`, and `COM1` to `COM3`, [Hewlett-Packard](/Hewlett-Packard_Company)'s OEM version of [MS-DOS 2.11](/MS-DOS_2.11) for the [HP Portable Plus](/HP_Portable_Plus) also supported `LST` as an alias for `LPT2` and `82164A` as an alias for `COM2`; it even included `PLT` for [plotters](/Plotter). More generally, `COM2`, `LPT2`, `LPT3`, and the `CLOCK$` (sometimes just `CLOCK` in certain [MS-DOS 2.11](/MS-DOS_2.11) issues) clock device were introduced with [DOS 2.0](/MS-DOS_2.0), while `COM3` and `COM4` were appended with [DOS 3.3](/MS-DOS_3.3). Only the rather ambitious, multitasking [MS-DOS 4](/MS-DOS_4.0_(multitasking)) dared to support `KEYBD$` and `SCREEN$`. [DR DOS 5.0](/DR_DOS_5.0) and its successors, along with [Multiuser DOS](/Multiuser_DOS), introduced an `IDLE$` device designed for dynamic idle detection, a clever mechanism to conserve power and enhance multitasking capabilities. `LPT4` is an optional, built-in driver for a fourth [line printer](/Parallel_port), supported in some versions of [DR-DOS](/DR-DOS) since 7.02. Finally, `CONFIG$` serves as the [real mode](/Real_mode) [PnP](/Legacy_Plug_and_Play) (Plug and Play) manager in [MS-DOS 7.0–8.0](/MS-DOS_7.0).

`AUX` typically defaulted to `COM1`, and `PRN` to `LPT1` (`LST`), but these defaults, in a rare nod to user flexibility, could be reconfigured in some DOS versions to point to other serial or parallel devices. The `PLT` device (exclusively found in certain [HP OEM](/Original_equipment_manufacturer) versions of [MS-DOS](/MS-DOS)) also offered this reconfigurability.

Filenames that deliberately end with a [colon](/Colon_(punctuation)) (`:`) such as `NUL:` conventionally serve as an explicit indication of device names. However, it's a critical distinction that the colon itself is *not* an intrinsic part of the name of the built-in device drivers. In many contexts, the colon isn't even necessary to type; for example, `ECHO This achieves nothing > NUL` works perfectly fine, demonstrating that DOS implicitly understands the intent when a reserved name is used in a device-like context.

Despite these strictures, it was, and in some archaic ways still is, possible to create files or directories using these very reserved device names. This could be achieved through direct, low-level manipulation of directory data structures within disk sectors, a method not for the faint of heart. Such unconventional naming, including the rather insidious trick of starting a filename with a space, has occasionally been exploited by malicious entities like viruses or hacking programs. Their goal? To obscure these files from unsuspecting users who, lacking the arcane knowledge of how to access these hidden locations, would remain blissfully unaware of their presence. It was a crude but effective form of digital camouflage.

### Memory management

Main article: [DOS memory management](/DOS_memory_management)

DOS was originally conceived and designed for the [Intel 8088 processor](/Intel_8088), a chip that, in its architectural limitations, could directly address a maximum of only 1 [MiB](/Mebibyte) of [RAM](/RAM). Both [IBM](/IBM) and [Microsoft](/Microsoft), in a decision that would haunt users for years, opted to allocate a mere 640 [kibibytes](/Kibibytes) (KiB) of this precious memory as the maximum available for application programs. The remaining 384 [KiB](/Kibibytes) was reserved, rather optimistically, for video memory, the [read-only memory](/Read-only_memory) (ROM) of adapter cards (such as those for video and network peripherals), and the system's core [BIOS](/BIOS). By the mid-1980s, the inevitable had occurred: many DOS applications, growing in complexity and ambition, were already bumping hard against this restrictive 640 [KiB](/Kibibytes) memory ceiling, even as significant portions of the reserved 384 [KiB](/Kibibytes) often lay fallow and unused, depending on the specific machine's configuration. It was a classic case of foresight failing to keep pace with innovation.

To circumvent these increasingly problematic memory limitations, a series of specifications were hastily developed to enable access to additional memory beyond the 1 [MiB](/Mebibyte) barrier. The first significant breakthrough was the [Expanded Memory Specification](/Expanded_Memory_Specification) (EMS). This ingenious, if convoluted, design allowed memory residing on specialized add-on cards to be accessed dynamically through a 64 [KiB](/Kibibytes) "page frame" located within the reserved upper memory area. Later, with the advent of [80386](/Intel_80386) and subsequent processor architectures, systems could leverage a [virtual 8086 mode](/Virtual_8086_mode) (V86) memory manager, such as [EMM386](/EMM386), to simulate expanded memory directly from existing extended memory, thereby obviating the need for expensive add-on cards.

The second crucial specification was the [Extended Memory Specification](/Extended_Memory_Specification) (XMS), developed for [80286](/Intel_80286) and later systems. This provided a more direct and efficient means to copy data to and from extended memory. It also granted access to the 65,520-byte [high memory area](/High_memory_area) (HMA), a curious sliver of memory located immediately above the first megabyte, and the [upper memory block](/Upper_memory_block) (UMB) area. Generally, XMS support was facilitated by the [HIMEM.SYS](/HIMEM.SYS) driver or by a [V86 mode](/Virtual_8086_mode) memory manager like [QEMM](/QEMM) or [386MAX](/386MAX), which often provided both EMS and XMS capabilities. It was a veritable alphabet soup of memory management, each acronym promising to unlock more digital real estate.

Beginning with [DOS 5](/MS-DOS_5.0), a welcome improvement arrived: DOS itself could directly capitalize on the [HMA](/High_memory_area) by loading its core kernel code and disk buffers into this precious space via the `DOS=HIGH` statement in [CONFIG.SYS](/CONFIG.SYS). This simple command freed up a significant chunk of conventional memory. Furthermore, [DOS 5+](/MS-DOS_5.0) also allowed for the utilization of available [upper memory blocks](/Upper_memory_block) (UMBs) through the `DOS=UMB` statement in [CONFIG.SYS](/CONFIG_SYS), further optimizing memory usage and making more of that coveted 640 [KiB](/Kibibytes) available to applications. It was a belated, but much-needed, attempt to make the most of the limited resources.

### DOS under OS/2 and Windows

See also: [Virtual DOS machine](/Virtual_DOS_machine)

The emulation of DOS within more advanced operating systems like [OS/2](/OS/2) and [Windows](/Microsoft_Windows) operates with remarkable fidelity, often behaving much like native applications within their respective host environments. These emulated DOS sessions gain access to all the host's available drives and services, and can even, with a touch of modern convenience, leverage the host's clipboard services. Because the fundamental drivers for file systems, network connectivity, and other low-level functions reside within the more robust host system, the DOS emulation layer primarily needs to provide a sophisticated DOS [API](/API) translation layer. This layer meticulously converts traditional DOS calls into the appropriate [OS/2](/OS/2) or [Windows](/Microsoft_Windows) system calls. Furthermore, this translation layer typically handles the conversion of [BIOS](/BIOS) calls and skillfully virtualizes the common I/O port accesses that many legacy DOS programs were prone to using directly.

In the era of [Windows 3.1](/Windows_3.1) and [Windows 9x](/Windows_9x), the DOS [virtual machine](/Virtual_machine) functionality was primarily delivered by a component known as WINOLDAP. This module meticulously created a virtual environment tailored to the specific DOS program, drawing its configuration from the program's associated PIF (Program Information File) and the overall system state at the moment Windows was launched. The DOS graphics mode, encompassing both character-based and graphical output, could be elegantly captured and displayed within a window on the Windows desktop. DOS applications, in a clever bridging of two worlds, could even utilize the Windows clipboard by accessing additional published calls within WINOLDAP, allowing users to seamlessly paste text between their DOS applications and Windows programs.

The emulated DOS environments found in [OS/2](/OS/2) and [Windows NT](/Windows_NT) were largely based upon the robust functionality of [DOS 5](/MS-DOS_5.0). While a default configuration ([CONFIG.SYS](/CONFIG.SYS) and [AUTOEXEC.BAT](/AUTOEXEC.BAT)) was always present, users possessed the flexibility to specify alternate configuration files on a session-by-session basis, allowing for tailored environments for different DOS applications. It was even possible to load specialized drivers within these configuration files to grant access to the host system's hardware, though these were typically third-party solutions, extending the reach of the virtual DOS environment.

Under [OS/2 2.x](/OS/2_2.0) and its subsequent iterations, the DOS emulation was provided by a powerful component called DOSKRNL. This file, in essence, represented the combined functionality of [IBMBIO.COM](/IBMBIO.COM) and [IBMDOS.COM](/IBMDOS_COM), with its system calls cleverly redirected through to the [OS/2](/OS/2) windowing services. DOS programs, ensconced in their own isolated environments, ran with impressive stability. The bulk of the DOS utilities themselves were supplied by "bound" DOS/[OS/2](/OS/2) applications residing within the `\OS2` directory, capable of running natively in either environment. [OS/2](/OS/2) also possessed the remarkable ability to execute [Windows 3.1](/Windows_3.1) applications by utilizing a modified copy of Windows, known as Win-OS/2. These modifications allowed [Windows 3.1](/Windows_3.1) programs to run seamlessly on the [OS/2](/OS/2) desktop, or alternatively, one could launch a dedicated WinOS/2 desktop, mirroring the experience of starting Windows directly from DOS.

[OS/2](/OS/2) also offered a unique feature dubbed 'DOS from Drive A:' (VMDISK). This wasn't merely an emulation; it was a way to boot a *real* DOS, such as [MS-DOS 6.22](/MS-DOS_6.22) or [PC DOS 5.00](/PC_DOS_5.00), within a virtual machine. The process involved creating a bootable floppy disk of the desired DOS version, adding a specific set of drivers from [OS/2](/OS/2), and then generating a special image file. The DOS booted in this manner had full, direct access to the system's hardware, but critically, it provided its own drivers for that hardware, bypassing the host's. This capability proved invaluable for tasks such as accessing [CD-ROM drives](/Optical_disc_drive) for which no native [OS/2](/OS/2) driver existed, a clever workaround for hardware compatibility challenges.

In all 32-bit (IA-32) editions of the [Windows NT family](/Windows_NT) since its inception in 1993, DOS emulation has been provided by means of a [virtual DOS machine](/Virtual_DOS_machine) (NTVDM). This robust subsystem allowed users to continue running their cherished 16-bit DOS applications in a modern environment. However, the march of progress, or perhaps just the relentless pursuit of deprecation, has its limits. 64-bit (IA-64 and x86-64) versions of Windows famously do *not* support NTVDM, rendering them incapable of directly executing 16-bit DOS applications. For those stubborn enough to cling to their legacy software on these newer machines, third-party [emulators](/Emulator) like [DOSBox](/DOSBox) remain the only viable recourse, proving that some digital ghosts simply refuse to be exorcised.

### User interface

DOS systems, in their unadorned glory, famously employed a stark and uncompromising [command-line interface](/Command-line_interface) (CLI). Interaction was a direct dialogue: a program was initiated by the simple, yet precise, act of entering its filename at the command prompt, followed by the obligatory press of the Enter key. DOS systems, in a gesture of helpfulness, included a suite of utility programs and provided a collection of internal commands that, rather than being distinct executables, were woven directly into the fabric of the command interpreter itself. It was a world of explicit commands and immediate feedback, a stark contrast to the point-and-click convenience that would eventually dominate.

In an earnest, and perhaps misguided, attempt to furnish a more user-friendly environment, a multitude of software manufacturers rose to the challenge, crafting sophisticated [file management programs](/File_manager) that offered users nascent [WIMP](/WIMP_(computing)) (Windows, Icons, Menus, Pointer) interfaces. [Microsoft Windows](/Microsoft_Windows) itself stands as the most notable example of this evolutionary trajectory, ultimately blossoming into [Microsoft Windows 9x](/Windows_9x), which effectively became a self-contained program loader, relegating DOS to a background role and usurping its position as the most widely used [PC-compatible](/IBM_PC_compatible) program loader. Beyond Windows, a thriving ecosystem of [text user interface](/Text_user_interface) (TUI) programs emerged, offering a more visually organized, yet still text-based, experience. These included the venerable [Norton Commander](/Norton_Commander), the feature-rich [DOS Navigator](/DOS_Navigator), the efficient [Volkov Commander](/Volkov_Commander), Quarterdeck's innovative [DESQview](/DESQview) (which offered a rudimentary form of multitasking), and the ever-present [Sidekick](/Borland_Sidekick) for quick notes and calculations. For those who craved true graphical interaction, [Graphical user interface](/Graphical_user_interface) (GUI) programs like [Digital Research](/Digital_Research)'s [GEM](/Graphics_Environment_Manager) (originally developed for [CP/M](/CP/M)) and [GEOS](/GEOS_(16-bit_operating_system)) provided a glimpse into a more visually rich future.

Eventually, even the manufacturers of the major DOS systems, recognizing the undeniable shift in user expectations, began to incorporate their own integrated environment managers. [MS-DOS](/MS-DOS)/[IBM DOS 4](/IBM_PC_DOS_4.0) included the rather utilitarian [DOS Shell](/DOS_Shell), a graphical file manager that offered a menu-driven interface. [DR DOS 5.0](/DR_DOS_5.0), released the following year, countered with [ViewMAX](/ViewMAX), a polished graphical environment based upon the aforementioned [GEM](/Graphics_Environment_Manager). These efforts, while perhaps too little, too late, demonstrated a grudging acknowledgment that the command line, for all its power, was not for everyone.

### Terminate and stay resident

Main article: [Terminate-and-stay-resident program](/Terminate-and-stay-resident_program)

Despite DOS's inherent design as a [single-tasking operating system](/Single-tasking_operating_system), a rather clever workaround emerged: the [terminate-and-stay-resident](/Terminate-and-stay-resident_program) (TSR) function. This ingenious mechanism allowed programs, after their primary execution, to remain resident in memory, effectively hovering in the background. These TSRs possessed the remarkable ability to "hook" into critical system interrupts, such as the system timer or keyboard interrupts. By doing so, they could periodically execute tasks in the background, or, more dramatically, be invoked at any moment, preempting the currently running foreground program. This effectively implemented a rudimentary form of multitasking, albeit on a program-specific, rather than operating-system-wide, basis. The DOS [PRINT](/PRINT_(command)) command, for instance, famously utilized this technique to provide background print spooling, allowing users to continue working while their documents slowly, noisily, emerged from the printer. [Borland Sidekick](/Borland_Sidekick), a popular popup [personal information manager](/Personal_information_manager) (PIM), also leveraged this technique, allowing users to access a calculator, calendar, or notepad with a simple keystroke, regardless of the foreground application.

[Terminate-and-stay-resident programs](/Terminate-and-stay-resident_program) also served a crucial role in extending DOS's functionality, providing additional features not available by default in the core operating system. Programs like CED (Command Line Editor) and [DOSKEY](/DOSKEY) offered sophisticated command-line editing facilities, far surpassing the basic capabilities embedded within [COMMAND.COM](/COMMAND.COM). Utilities such as the Microsoft CD-ROM Extensions ([MSCDEX](/MSCDEX)) were essential TSRs, providing the necessary software layer for DOS to access files residing on [CD-ROM disks](/Optical_disc_drive).

Some particularly advanced [TSRs](/Terminate-and-stay-resident_program) even managed to perform a rudimentary form of task switching. Consider, for example, the [shareware](/Shareware) program Back and Forth (circa 1990). This utility allowed users, via a designated hotkey, to save the entire state of the currently running program to disk, then load and switch to another program. This enabled users to switch "back and forth" between applications, albeit with noticeable delays due to the necessary disk access involved in saving and restoring program states. Crucially, Back and Forth could not, on its own, enable true [background processing](/Background_process); that more sophisticated capability required a dedicated environment like [DESQview](/DESQview), especially on systems with at least an [Intel 80386](/Intel_80386) processor, which provided the necessary hardware support for virtual memory and protected mode operations.

## Software

For those truly dedicated to cataloging the digital past, further information can be found in [Category:DOS software](/Category:DOS_software).

The DOS era, despite its technical limitations, was a fertile ground for software development, giving rise to applications that defined personal computing for a generation.

*   [Arachne](/Arachne_(web_browser)), a pioneering 16-bit graphical [web browser](/Web_browser) that, against all odds, brought the early internet to DOS machines.
*   [dBase](/DBase), a powerful [database](/Database) program that became a standard for data management, allowing businesses to organize and query vast amounts of information.
*   [Harvard Graphics](/Harvard_Graphics), a presentation graphics design program that empowered users to create professional-looking charts and slides, long before PowerPoint became ubiquitous.
*   [Lotus 1-2-3](/Lotus_1-2-3), a revolutionary [spreadsheet](/Spreadsheet) application that is widely credited with being a primary catalyst for the widespread success of the [IBM PC](/IBM_PC) itself, making number crunching accessible to the masses.
*   [Norton Commander](/Norton_Commander) and [XTree](/XTree), indispensable file management utilities that offered a visual, menu-driven alternative to the command line, making file navigation far less painful.
*   [PKZIP](/PKZIP), the utility that rapidly became the undisputed standard in file compression, an essential tool for managing the ever-growing size of digital files in an era of limited storage and slow transfers.
*   [ProComm](/ProComm), [Qmodem](/Qmodem), and [Telix](/Telix), a trio of essential [modem](/Modem) communication programs that served as gateways to the nascent online world of bulletin board systems and early internet access.
*   [Sidekick](/Borland_Sidekick), a groundbreaking [personal information manager](/Personal_information_manager) (PIM) that famously operated as a [TSR](/Terminate-and-stay-resident_program), allowing it to be instantly invoked and used from within virtually any other program.
*   [WordPerfect](/WordPerfect), a dominant [word processor](/Word_processor) throughout the 1980s, beloved for its powerful features and keyboard-centric interface, before it was eventually overshadowed by graphical alternatives.
*   [WordStar](/WordStar), a word processor that, despite its origins on [CP/M](/CP/M), achieved immense popularity on the [IBM PC](/IBM_PC), becoming a staple for professional writing.

### Development tools

The DOS platform also fostered a vibrant ecosystem of development tools, allowing programmers to craft the applications that defined the era.

*   Various [BASIC](/BASIC) language interpreters, including [BASICA](/BASICA) and [GW-BASIC](/GW-BASIC), provided an accessible entry point into programming for countless enthusiasts.
*   [DJGPP](/DJGPP), a remarkable 32-bit [DPMI](/DPMI) DOS port of the [GNU Compiler Collection](/GNU_Compiler_Collection) ([gcc](/GNU_Compiler_Collection)), brought modern C/C++ development to the DOS environment.
*   [Microsoft Macro Assembler](/Microsoft_Macro_Assembler), [Microsoft C](/Microsoft_C), and [CodeView](/CodeView) from [Microsoft](/Microsoft) formed a comprehensive suite for professional software development.
*   [Watcom C/C++](/Watcom_C/C%2B%2B) from [Watcom](/Watcom), renowned for its optimizing compilers, was a favorite among game developers for its ability to generate fast, efficient code.
*   [Turbo Pascal](/Turbo_Pascal), [Turbo BASIC](/Turbo_BASIC), [Turbo C](/Turbo_C), [Turbo Prolog](/Turbo_Prolog), and [Turbo Assembler](/Turbo_Assembler) from [Borland](/Borland), a legendary suite of integrated development environments that revolutionized programming by offering fast compilation and intuitive interfaces.

